 blank" data-catid="19"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-introductory-tutorial/">Bodysuit with Corset Cups <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="24"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-measurement/">Party Dress <span>(17)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#544">Transparent corsets  <span>(4)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="25"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-cutting-a-mock-up/">Corset with Drapery <span>(20)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="26"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-and-the-throw-over-sewing-technique/">Corset with Integral Straps <span>(27)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="34"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model/">Corset with 3-Part Cups <span>(22)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="76"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-5/">Corset with a Fancy Cut-Out <span>(22)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#3082">Decoration Techniques  <span>(9)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="83"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials/">Rhinestones Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="84"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-glue-on-half-pearls/">Additional Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="85"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-thick-decoration-element/">Thick Decoration Elements <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="86"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong>Dressmaker’s Treasury will equip you with a range of necessary tools and techniques which every professional must possess for successful work.</strong></p><p><strong>It will help you get more confident. You will know how to: </strong></p><ul><li>Choose the right strategy for making a garment after your first meeting with the client;</li><li>Take necessary measurements correctly and prepare and fill out an order form;</li><li>Choose the right basic pattern and adjust it after your client’s measurements with the help of automatic pattern adjustments calculation tables;</li><li>Avoid common mistakes which result in ill-fitting necklines by choosing the right sewing technique.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;5h 16m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-10-mistakes-caused-by-the-wrong-choice-of-pattern-boat-neckline/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-10-mistakes-caused-by-the-wrong-choice-of-pattern-boat-neckline/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2017-11-30T17:12:10+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2017-11-30T17:12:10+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2017"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 10. Mistakes Caused by the Wrong Choice of Pattern. Boat Neckline."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 10. Mistakes Caused by the Wrong Choice of Pattern. Boat Neckline."><meta itemprop="description" content="We are starting the most important chapter of the book in which you will learn how to choose your patterns correctly with regard to the desired garment style"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding and Evening Dresses. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding and evening dresses. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 10. Mistakes Caused by the Wrong Choice of Pattern. Boat Neckline.</h1><p><strong>We are starting the most important chapter of the book in which you will learn how to choose your patterns correctly with regard to the desired garment style. </strong></p><p><strong>I want you to know </strong>that most mistakes which result in a poor fit are caused by the wrong choice of sewing pattern.</p><p>Yes, not even the wrong choice of sewing technique but the wrong choice of sewing pattern.</p><p><strong>I talked about it a lot in my first courses, as well as in the first edition of “Dressmaker’s Treasury.” </strong>But a lot of time has gone since then and there are many new courses at the Corset Academy.</p><p>I know it for sure that many people purchase a certain course to sew the exact garment it is dedicated to for themselves or for a client. You can always see a picture of the garment on the cover.</p><p><strong>The dress is made! Everything worked out just great! </strong>And the dressmaker keeps all patterns included in the course for future work.</p><p><strong>After some time, the dressmaker accepts an order from a new client. </strong>The style of the garment is obviously different from the garment previously made following the guidelines from the course.</p><p>And yet very often the dressmaker just takes the same pattern, slightly alters it to match the new style, and starts sewing a totally new garment.</p><p><strong>I suppose you can guess what happens next. </strong>The dressmaker is sincerely puzzled and cannot understand why nothing works, why the previous dress had a perfect fit, and the new garment just refuses to fit nicely?</p><p><strong>The answer is obvious: </strong>this pattern is not suitable for sewing this garment!</p><p><strong>In this course, we will discuss each pattern type step by step so you can get things clear with that stock of patterns you have accumulated throughout the years, as well as the patterns you have received with this book. </strong></p><p><strong>This book is called “Dressmaker’s Treasury” for a reason! </strong></p><p><strong>It contains those patterns which every seamstress must have in stock! </strong>This basic set of patterns is enough for sewing almost any garment possible.</p><p><strong>The question is what pattern to choose for each particular garment? </strong></p><p><strong>For example, you have a pattern of a corset with two front princess seams each of which divides one half or one side of the front in two. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2010.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>We will focus on the front for a start. </strong></p><p><strong>There are no intermediate princess seams at the front. This pattern has few degrees of variance so to say. </strong>There are two bust princess seams and nothing more.</p><p>In other words, either half of the front is made of two pieces: centre front and side front.</p><p>It is much harder to adjust this pattern after client’s measurements than it is with patterns which have several degrees of variance thanks to additional princess seams.</p><p><strong>I offer you three versions of this particular pattern with three different neckline styles: V-neck, boat neck, and straight neck or strapless. </strong>These are basically the three pillars of all corset patterns.</p><p><strong>First of all, let us compare the front pieces of these three versions. </strong></p><p><strong>Take the boat neck pattern. Let us compare its front pieces with those of the V-neck pattern and the strapless pattern. </strong></p><p><strong>I take the side front pieces. </strong></p><p><strong>I put together the boat neck side front piece and the strapless side front piece. </strong>Their side seam shape, princess seam shape, and cup shape are basically the same.</p><p><strong>They are only different at the top: </strong>the strapless piece has a slant down to the side seam while the boat neck piece has an upward corner (see below).</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2010.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Let us look at the centre front pieces. </strong></p><p><strong>I put together the boat neck centre front piece and the strapless centre front piece. </strong>It is the same story here. Their side seam, princess seam, and cup are the same. The only difference is found at the top.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2010.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>And now let us compare the front pieces of the boat neck pattern and the V-neck pattern. </strong></p><p><strong>Centre front pieces: </strong></p><p><strong>There is a rather noticeable difference between these two patterns. </strong>When I align them along the main lines, I can see that there is a difference in the incline of the bust princess seam apart from the difference at the top naturally occurring because of unlike neckline shapes. In other words, the princess seam dart on the centre front piece of the boat neck pattern is not the same as on the centre front piece of the V-neck pattern. It has a slightly wider opening on the V-neck piece.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2010.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Side front pieces: </strong></p><p><strong>These pieces differ from each other even more noticeably. </strong>The boat neck piece has a straighter vertical edge than the V-neck piece. Besides, the opening of the dart is a lot wider on the V-neck side front piece than on the boat neck side front piece.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2010.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I also want you to note that the difference in the opening of the bust princess seam dart is not the same on the centre front piece of the V-neck pattern as on the side front piece! </strong>It is 0.5cm on the centre front piece and 2cm on the side front piece.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2010.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>It is therefore completely wrong to assume </strong>that it would be enough to deepen the bust princess seam dart in the cup area to achieve a good fit of the V-shaped neckline in the bust if you tried to use the pattern of the boat neck front for sewing a V-neck corset.</p><p>No, it would not work! And this is no accident! All these patterns are the result of many years of work, test, and trial, a synthesis of all my sewing experience. Believe me, these dart opening widths were not calculated to match a certain difference between Bust Circumference and Under-Bust Circumference. <strong>My key goal during the making of these patterns was to ensure the best fit in the décolleté area. </strong></p><p>Of course, highly experienced dressmakers who are familiar with the laws of pattern-making and particularly corset-making know how to adjust a standard pattern and adapt it for a certain style. They have a sense for it. Experience points out many small details which help you achieve a perfect fit.</p><p><strong>But my tried-and-true patterns will be very helpful for beginners and for dressmakers who are only getting started with corset garments! </strong></p><p>For this reason, I would like to draw your attention back to the right choice of pattern suitable for each particular garment.</p><p><strong>Here is, for example, what happened to one of my students. </strong>I received an E-mail with pictures of a garment in which my student complained that she made a corset using my patterns and guidelines and it turned out to have a poor fit in the bust: the neckline did not cling to the body.</p><p><strong>I examined her pictures very attentively and, frankly speaking, I couldn’t recognize my pattern! </strong>I was wondering what went wrong because nothing like this had ever happened before! What did it all mean? The dressmaker claimed she had used my pattern.</p><p>I could tell it from the pictures that she followed the right sewing technique: the cups were eased-in correctly in all required areas. Even if my student had made a mistake in pattern adjustment calculations, it would not have affected the fit of the neckline in the bust because pattern adjustment areas are normally located below the bust line.</p><p><strong>My patterns are carefully designed to provide a great fit both on the dress-form, as well as on any woman. </strong></p><p>If you change the pattern widthwise or change the clip measurement to make the cups deeper or shallower, it will not affect the good fit in the bust.</p><p><strong>And then I began to understand what happened and why my student’s corset did not cling to the bust! </strong>When I asked her what pattern exactly she had used, it turned out she had used a pattern with a boat-neck front for a corset with a V-neck front!</p><p><strong>Let me demonstrate what will happen to the front of a corset sewn after the boat neck pattern if you cut a V-neck in it. </strong></p><p><strong>I cut a “V’ in my boat-neck mock-up.</strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2010.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>You can see it in the picture that the neckline edge does not cling to the bust. And there is no way to fix this, no easing-in or any other technique will help!</strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2010.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>What happens next is a true disaster! </strong>You can try to remove that excess fabric with the help of the bust princess seams. But even something like this can only be done if you have a mock-up which you can put on the dress-form.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2010.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>In reality, here is what happens. </strong></p><p>You are sewing a corset for a certain woman and it is hard to do fittings on the dress-form because it is not the same as a real person.</p><p><strong>As a rule, your client comes to try the garment on when it is nearly finished. </strong></p><p>And then you see this awful effect when the corset is simply loose in the bust! And you have already reinforced the cups with bones and duplicated them with woven interfacing. You have already put bones along the neckline edges, too. You have carefully pressed and steamed the corset, which means the pattern already got deformed and you cannot make it tighter in the décolleté area.</p><p><strong>What conclusion can you make in this situation? </strong>Do you know? You must confess that you went the wrong way from the very start by choosing the wrong pattern. It is hard to accept this thought! And, therefore, there is only one conclusion left: I did everything right but this pattern was just bad!</p><p><strong>To make all doubts fade away, let me ask you one simple question: </strong>would a professional dressmaker sew a jacket after a blouse pattern and then blame everything on a “bad” blouse pattern?</p><p><strong>Of course not! </strong>Similarly, there is a difference between patterns of corsets with different necklines. It may be not as significant as between a jacket and a blouse, and yet it does matter.</p><p><strong>I really hope you will never find yourself in a situation like this! </strong></p><p>I have only described one mistake for now but we will talk about other possible mistakes and ways to prevent them in the tutorials to follow.</p><p><strong>This is why I consider it the key task of this book to teach you how to choose the right sewing pattern from the beginning!</strong></p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p><p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20boat.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Boat-Neck Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20strapless.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Strapless Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20V%20neck.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> V-Neck Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/corset%20-%20neck%20strap.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Corset with Halter-Neck Strap</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/corset%20-%20shoulder%20strap.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Corset with Shoulder Strap</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/corset%20-%20straight%20cut.pdf" target="_blank"